Exercise 1

Use the prostate cancer data (Stamey et al., 1989) to train a model that predicts log of prostate-specific antigen. Investigate how to perform. In the publication, they examined the correlation between the level of prostate-specific antigen (PSA) and a number of clinical measures in men who were about to receive a radical prostatectomy. PSA is a protein that is produced by the prostate gland. The higher a manâs PSA level, the more likely it is that he has prostate cancer.

The variables are log cancer volume (lcavol), log prostate weight (lweight), age, log of the amount of benign prostatic hyperplasia (lbph), seminal vesicle invasion (svi), log of capsular penetration (lcp), Gleason score (gleason), and percent of Gleason scores 4 or 5 (pgg45).

Do not forget to perform subset selection of the features!

EDA

Checking the correlation of the variables, there arenât any evident correlations that could be used to eliminate the first less important variables.

ggpairs(pros_data)

Since some of the variables already have a conversion (logarithm), I donât make any preprocessing step. Then, I proceed to make the data split and perform linear regression with feature selection using different algorithms from the package leaps to compare between them. In all of them I perform 5-fold cross-validation and grid searches from 1 to 10 to find the number of variables that yields the minimum Root Mean Square Error (RMSE).

trainid <- createDataPartition(pros_data$lpsa, p = .75, list = F, times = 1)

training <- pros_data[trainid,]
# training[,-1:-2] <- scale(training[,-1:-2])

testing <- pros_data[-trainid,]
# testing[,-1:-2] <- scale(testing[,-1:-2])


Linear regression with backwards feature selection

set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="grid", 
                       returnData=T, savePredictions=T, classProbs=T,
                       summaryFunction = defaultSummary,
                       selectionFunction = function(x, metric="RMSE", maximize=F) {best(x, metric, maximize)} )

back_model <- train(lpsa ~ ., data=training, method="leapBackward", metric="RMSE", trControl=crossv,
                    tuneGrid=data.frame("nvmax"=c(1:10)))

results <- grid.arrange(tableGrob( back_model$bestTune, rows="best" ),
                        tableGrob( data.frame("coefficients"=coef(back_model$finalModel, back_model$bestTune$nvmax)) ),
                        nrow=1)
grid.arrange( ggplot(back_model) + labs(title = "Backwards Feature Selection"), 
              results, nrow=2, heights=c(1, back_model$bestTune$nvmax*0.175))

For linear regression with backwards feature selection the optimal number of variables found is 3: lcavol, lweight, age.

back_pred <- predict(back_model, testing)

back_metrics <- data.frame("backwards"=postResample(pred = back_pred, obs = testing$lpsa))


Linear regression with forward feature selection

set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="grid", 
                       returnData=T, savePredictions=T, classProbs=T,
                       summaryFunction = defaultSummary,
                       selectionFunction = function(x, metric="RMSE", maximize=F) {best(x, metric, maximize)} )

fwd_model <- train(lpsa ~ ., data=training, method="leapForward", metric="RMSE", trControl=crossv,
                   tuneGrid=data.frame("nvmax"=c(1:10)))

results <- grid.arrange(tableGrob( fwd_model$bestTune, rows="best" ),
                        tableGrob( data.frame("coefficients"=coef(fwd_model$finalModel, fwd_model$bestTune$nvmax)) ),
                        nrow=1)
grid.arrange( ggplot(fwd_model) + labs(title = "Forward Feature Selection"), 
              results, nrow=2, heights=c(1, fwd_model$bestTune$nvmax*0.175))

For linear regression with forward feature selection. the optimal number of variables found is 2 and they are also present in the subset of variables selected with the Backwards method: lcavol, lweight.

fwd_pred <- predict(fwd_model, testing)

fwd_metrics <- data.frame("forwards"=postResample(pred = fwd_pred, obs = testing$lpsa))


Linear regression with stepwise feature selection

set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="grid", 
                       returnData=T, savePredictions=T, classProbs=T,
                       summaryFunction = defaultSummary,
                       selectionFunction = function(x, metric="RMSE", maximize=F) {best(x, metric, maximize)} )

step_model <- train(lpsa ~ ., data=training, method="leapSeq", metric="RMSE", trControl=crossv,
                    tuneGrid=data.frame("nvmax"=c(1:10)))

results <- grid.arrange(tableGrob( step_model$bestTune, rows="best" ),
                        tableGrob( data.frame("coefficients"=coef(step_model$finalModel, step_model$bestTune$nvmax)) ),
                        nrow=1)
grid.arrange( ggplot(step_model) + labs(title = "Stepwise Feature Selection"), 
              results, nrow=2, heights=c(1, step_model$bestTune$nvmax*0.175))

For linear regression with stepwise feature selection. the optimal number of variables found is 2, and they are the same that were selected with the Forward method: lcavol, lweight.

step_pred <- predict(step_model, testing)

step_metrics <- data.frame("stepwise"=postResample(pred = step_pred, obs = testing$lpsa))


Comparison

cplot <- ggplot(mapping=aes(x=testing$lpsa, y=back_pred)) +
  
  geom_point() + stat_smooth(method="lm", se=F) + theme_classic() +
  
  labs(title="Correlation",
       subtitle="Prediction with Linear regression with Backwards feature selection",
       x="Observed log(lpsa)",
       y="Predicted log(lpsa)")

ctable <- as.data.frame(rbind(t(back_metrics), t(fwd_metrics), t(step_metrics)))

grid.arrange( tableGrob( ctable[,c("RMSE", "Rsquared")] ), cplot, nrow=2, heights=c(0.175*3,1))

As the variables selected by the Forwards and Stepwise algorithms are the same, the calculated coefficients are also the same and so are the predictions. In contrast, the subset of variables selected by the Backwards algorithm yields slightly better RMSE and R2 values for the predictions. However, the calculated R2 for the predictions with the Backwards algorithm (0.59) is not high enough and might indicate that this (and also the other two) isnât a very good model. On the other hand, the dataset is rather small (97 observations) and there is a high difference between the minimum RMSE found for the optimal number of variables for the Backwards algorithm (0.7180693) and the calculated RMSE for the predictions (0.7972736), so the number of observations may not be enough for a good averaging and the model may be overfitting the training dataset.

Linear regression without selection

set.seed(1)

lm_model <- train(lpsa ~ ., data=training, method="lm", metric="RMSE")

# grid.arrange( tableGrob( t(data.frame("coefficients"=coef(lm_model$finalModel))) ) )

lm_pred <- predict(lm_model, testing)


grid.arrange( tableGrob( t(data.frame("train error"=t(lm_model$results[2:4]))), rows="train.error" ),
              tableGrob( t(data.frame("test error"=postResample(pred = lm_pred, obs = testing$lpsa))) ),
              nrow=2)

Now, using all variables as predictors, the RMSE of the training and test sets are more similar and even the R2 of the test set is higher than the one of the training set, so the overfitting may not be happening. The results are still not good enough, so the reason may be the small size of the dataset. An RMSE of around 0.8 is around the 32% of the mean of the target variable lpsa (2.5).

After checking the correlation, there are many correlated variables, and I will use caretâs own findCorrelation function to automatically select and delete the redundant variables. Then, I separate the dataset 75/25 with caretâs createDataPartition stratifying for the diagnosis variable and scale the samples separately.

todelete <- findCorrelation( cor(bc_data[,-1:-2]), exact=T ) + 2

bc_data_red <- bc_data[,-todelete]


trainid <- createDataPartition(bc_data_red$diagnosis, p = .75, list = F, times = 1)

training <- bc_data_red[trainid,]
training[,-1:-2] <- scale(training[,-1:-2])

testing <- bc_data_red[-trainid,]
testing[,-1:-2] <- scale(testing[,-1:-2])


K-nearest neighbours

set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="grid", 
                       returnData=T, savePredictions=T, classProbs=T,
                       summaryFunction = multiClassSummary,
                       selectionFunction = function(x, metric="F1", maximize=T) {best(x, metric, maximize)} )

bc_knn_model <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data=training[,-1], method="knn", metric="F1", trControl=crossv, 
                      tuneGrid=data.frame("k"=seq(1, dim(training)[1], 1)))

grid.arrange( ggplot(bc_knn_model) + labs(title = "K-neighbours hyperparameter optimization"), 
              tableGrob(bc_knn_model$bestTune, rows="best"), nrow=2, heights=c(1,0.15))

pred_knn <- predict(bc_knn_model, testing) 

knn_cm <- confusionMatrix(pred_knn, testing$diagnosis, mode = "everything")
knn_cm <- data.frame( knn = c(knn_cm$overall[1], knn_cm$byClass) )
roc_df <- bc_knn_model$pred[bc_knn_model$pred$k == bc_knn_model$bestTune$k,]

rocplot <- ggplot(roc_df, aes(m = M, d = factor(obs, levels = c("B", "M")))) +
  
  geom_roc(hjust = -0.5, vjust = 2) + coord_equal() + theme_classic() +
  
  labs(title = "ROC curve of k-NN classification model",
       x = "False positive rate", y = "True positive rate") + style_roc()

rocplot

A search of all possible values of the nearest neighbours hyperparameter finds the optimal to be 1, using F-score as the metric. The ROC curve below also has a great shape, with an area under the curve of 0.94.

Decision tree

set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="random", returnData=T,
                       summaryFunction = multiClassSummary,

grid.arrange( ggplot(bc_tree_model) + labs(title = "Complexity hyperparameter optimization"),

For a decision tree, the random search of also size 100 finds the best value of the complexity hyperparameter to be 0.0314, using F-score as the metric. The variables that are chosen for the final tree are the âworstâ mean value of the number of concave portions of the contour of the nuclei (concave.points_worst) and the mean area of the nuclei of the cell (area_mean).

pred <- predict(bc_tree_model, testing)

fancyRpartPlot(bc_tree_model$finalModel, type=2, sub="")


Random forest

tuning <- data.frame(splitrule = "gini",
                     mtry = sample( 1 : 20, size=20, replace=F ),
                     min.node.size = sample( 1 : 20, size=200, replace=T))
set.seed(1)
crossv <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number=5, repeats=5, search="grid", returnData=T,
                       summaryFunction = multiClassSummary,
                       selectionFunction = function(x, metric="F1", maximize=T) {best(x, metric, maximize)} )

bc_forest_model <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data=training[,-1], method="ranger", metric="F1", trControl=crossv, tuneGrid=tuning)

grid.arrange( ggplot(bc_forest_model) + guides(color=guide_legend(ncol=2)) +
                labs(title = "Random forest hyperparameter optimization",
                     subtitle = "Minimal node size and number of randomly selected predictors; trees analyzed with Gini index"), 
              tableGrob(bc_forest_model$bestTune, rows="best"), 
              nrow=2, heights=c(1,0.15))

pred <- predict(bc_forest_model, testing) 

forest_cm <- confusionMatrix(pred, testing$diagnosis, mode = "everything")
forest_cm <- data.frame( forest = c(forest_cm$overall[1], forest_cm$byClass) )

The random forest algorithm of the ranger package has three hyperparameters: the metric to evaluate the importance of the splits in the trees (splitrule), the number of randomly selected variables to use to build the trees (mtry) and the minimum node size at which to stop the splitting (min.node.size). In this case, I have selected the Gini index to be the split metric and performed a grid search for the other two. The number of variables can only be a maximum of 20, and for each possible number of variables 10 random node sizes between 1 and 20 have been evaluated. The best number of randomly selected variables to use to build trees is 3 and of minimum node size is 4.

Comparison

metrics <- 
  as.data.frame(rbind(t(knn_cm), t(tree_cm), t(forest_cm), t(logreg_cm))) %>%
  
  rownames_to_column() %>%
  rename(`F-score`=F1) %>%
  
  gather(`Accuracy`, `F-score`, `Specificity`, `Sensitivity`, `Detection Rate`, key="metric", value="value") %>%
  
  mutate(rowname = as.factor(rowname)) %>%
  mutate(rowname = factor(rowname,levels(rowname)[c(2,4,1,3)])) %>%
  
  mutate(metric = as.factor(metric)) %>%
  mutate(metric = factor(metric,levels(metric)[c(5,3,1,4,2)]))


ggplot(metrics) +
  
  stat_summary(aes(x=as.factor(rowname), y=value, group=metric, color=metric), fun.y=sum, geom="line", size=1.125) +
  
  scale_color_OkabeIto() + theme_classic() + 
  
  labs(title = "Prediction quality metrics comparison between models", x="", y="") +
  
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("k-NN", "Decision tree", "Random\nforest", "Logistic\nregression")) +
  
  theme(legend.title = element_blank(), 
        axis.text = element_text(size=rel(1.125), color="black"),
        legend.text = element_text(size=rel(1.125), color="black"))

Surprisingly, the best performing model is the logistic regression, which is the simplest one. The random forest model is the runner-up with very similar values for the prediction quality metrics shown.
